Excerpt from a CNN article: "The Chinese government has issued new regulations to severely punish people who disrupt the epidemic control work. Those who violate the rules will be subject to speedy arrests and sentences, and even the death penalty."
Well, I strongly advocate that, that should be RETROACTIVE to include those responsible for halting Dr Li Wenliang's efforts to expose the truth just so to protect the CCP's "all is well in China" mantra. Things would have turned out so differently -- much better most probably -- had the TRUTH been allowed to be known. But here we are confronted with thousands upon thousands of infections AND deaths, as expected, on a daily basis.
One would think that China has learned its lesson from its SARS debacle, but sadly, that's not the case. The CCP's "image" remains top priority... even at the cost of human lives, regardless of nationality.

#StopCensorshipInChina
#HeroLiWenliang

snippet.textDisplay:
This is the first article that actually worries me. I mean, he was 34, was among the first people to be aware of the virus (and look what China did to him when he tried to warn people back in December), a doctor (so I'm assuming he was aware of and practiced basic principles of infection control like handwashing), checked himself into a hospital after just one day of coughing, but he still died a month later.

I guess what I'm saying is people shouldn't take this outbreak too lightly. Stop minimizing it due to that 2.1% fatality rate figure (posted below). H1N1 had a 0.02% fatality rate yet it killed 284,500 people in a year. Do your best to prevent catching and spreading 2019-nCoV by following WHO and CDC prevention guidelines. Maybe avoiding heavy crowds for the time being isn't such a ridiculous idea. An ounce of prevention...

Don't panic, but don't tempt fate, either.”
